Part 0: From Tests to Models¶

Intro: Statistical Modeling¶

  • So far, we've focused on hypothesis tests.
    • I.e., "Is a difference between groups significant?"
  • But statistics also gives us tools to model our data.
  • A "statistical model" is a very powerful and versatile concept:
    • Prediction: how can we make better predictions of $Y$, given $X$ and parameters $\beta$?
    • Inference: what theoretical inferences can we make about the relationship between $X$ and $Y$, given $\beta$?
  • NHST philosophy can be applied to interpretation of parameters $\beta$ (coming up later).

Models as generative¶

  • Statistical models are also generative.
  • Underlying assumptions:
    • Observed data $X, Y$ was the result of some data-generating process.
    • We can't know this process exactly, but we can build a model of it.
    • "All models are wrong, but some are useful".
  • This is what allows us to generate new output from a statistical model.

Looking ahead: ML models¶

  • The notion of a "model" is very important for machine learning.

  • In supervised learning, we learn a function mapping input to labeled output.

    $\Large Y = f(X, \beta) + \epsilon$

  • Model fitting refers to a procedure for finding parameters $\beta$ that lead to the best predictions of $Y$, given $X$.
  • One of the simplest and most prevalent models is linear regression.

Part 1: Intro to linear regression¶

Linear regression¶

  • Goal: find the best-fitting line between $X$ and $Y$.
    • Assuming a linear relationship bewteen inputs $X$ and response $Y$...
    • ...find parameters $\beta$ that minimize prediction error.

  • Allows for multiple predictor variables (and thus multiple parameters or coefficients).

    $\Large Y = \beta_1X_1 + \beta_2X_2 + ... + \beta_nX_n $

Check-in: why linear regression?¶

Check-in: why linear regression?¶

Answer: Linear regression uses a linear equation. It assumes the function between $X$ and $Y$ is linear.

$\Large Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1X_1 + \epsilon$

  • $\beta_0$, or intercept: predicted $\hat{Y}$ when $X_1 = 0$.
  • $\beta_1$, or slope: predicted increase in $\hat{Y}$ for each 1-unit increase in $X_1$.
    • When $X_1$ is categorical, slope (typically) reflects the difference in means between categories.
  • $\epsilon$, or error: assumes normally-distributed "leftover variance".

Making connections: Regression and NHST¶

  • Our parameters $\beta_0, \beta_1, ..., \beta_n$ are estimates.
  • Underlying assumption: there is some truly linear, data-generating process.
    • We don't know the true parameter valuesjust like we never know the population parameter.
    • Instead, we must estimate them from a sample.

Linear equation in action¶

The linear equation uses parameters $\beta$ to generate output $Y$ from input $X$.

  • Note 1: This generative model is missing an error term, $\epsilon$.
  • Note 2: In practice, these parameters are learned from labeled data $[X, Y]$.
  • As the plot shows, the output is linear.
In [3]:
X = np.arange(1, 101) ### Given some inputs X...
beta = 2.5 ### some coefficient
intercept = 1 ### and some intercept
y_pred = X*beta + intercept ### we can generate predictions
plot = plt.scatter(X, y_pred)

Assumption 1: Linearity¶

  • At its core, linear regression assumes a linear relationship between $X$ and $Y$.
  • This is a very major assumption!
    • Lots of relationships aren't linear.
  • This is an example of a model with high bias: it makes a strong assumption about functional form.

Why the linear bias matters¶

If we fit a linear model to each of these datasets, the slope coefficient would be roughly identicaleven though the datasets are clearly very different.

In [4]:
df_anscombe = sns.load_dataset('anscombe')
sns.lmplot(data = df_anscombe,
           x = 'x',
           y = 'y',
           col = 'dataset')
Out[4]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7f7d39ec7280>

Models do what they're told, even when you don't want them to.¶

  • Even if a non-linear relationship is clear to us, linear regression will always try to find a linear relationship.
  • In Statistical Rethinking, Richard McElreath compares statistical models to "golems".
    • Powerful machines that follow their instructions to the letter.
    • This is also true of traditional hypothesis tests.
  • Note 1: some models (like deep neural networks) have more flexibility, while others (like linear regression), have less.
    • This is at the heart of the bias-variance trade-off.

What is the "line of best fit"?¶

  • Linear regression tries to find the best-fitting line between $X$ and $Y$.

What does this mean?¶

Many possible lines between $X$ and $Y$¶

These lines all begin in the same place, but have different slopes.

In [7]:
plt.scatter(X, Y, alpha = .5)
for coef in [1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 3]:
    y_pred = X * coef
    plt.plot(X, y_pred, alpha = .8, linestyle = "dotted")

Clearly, some lines are "better" than others.¶

  • We can quantify quality of fit by calculating prediction error in some way.

  • Simple approach: sum of squared deviations (residuals) between predictions $\hat{Y}$ and actual values $Y$.

    $\Large RSS = \sum_i^N (\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2$

Does this equation remind you of anything?

Analogy: $SS_X$ vs. $RSS$¶

The sum of squares of X is defined as:

  • $\Large SS_X = \sum_{i}^{N}(x_i - \mu)^2$

Whereas RSS is defined as:

  • $\Large RSS = \sum_i^N (\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2$

Comparing $RSS$ for different lines¶

  • Lowest (best) RSS when $\beta = 2$, which we know was the true parameter value.
In [8]:
errors = []
for coef in [1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 3]:
    rss = sum((X * coef - Y)**2) ## Get SSE
    errors.append({'rss': rss, 'slope': coef}) ## Add to dictionary
df_errors = pd.DataFrame(errors)
sns.barplot(data = df_errors, x = 'slope', y = 'rss')
plt.xlabel("Slope coefficient")
plt.ylabel("RSS")
Out[8]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'RSS')

A more interpretable measure¶

  • The standard error of the estimate provides a more interpretable measure of prediction error.

    $\Large S_{Y|X} = \sqrt{\frac{RSS}{n-2}}$

  • $S_{Y|X}$ tells us (roughly) the average amount of prediction error.
    • How much, on average, do we expect $\hat{Y}$ to deviate from $Y$?
    • As before, a smaller number means better fit.

$S_{Y|X}$ in action (pt. 1)¶

In [9]:
errors = []
for coef in [1, 1.5, 2, 2.5, 3]:
    see = math.sqrt(sum((X * coef - Y)**2)/(len(X)-2)) ## Get SEE
    errors.append({'see': see, 'slope': coef}) ## Add to dictionary
df_errors = pd.DataFrame(errors)
sns.barplot(data = df_errors, x = 'slope', y = 'see')
plt.xlabel("Slope coefficient")
plt.ylabel("Standard error of the estimate")
Out[9]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Standard error of the estimate')

$S_{Y|X}$ in action (pt. 2)¶

  • $S_{Y|X}$ tells us which parameters yield the best fit.
  • We can also use $S_{Y|X}$ to attach uncertainty to specific predictions!

Given that $X = 10$, we predict that $\hat{Y} = 20, \pm 12.03$.

  • In principle, this also allows us to give confidence intervals for each prediction.

Given that $X = 10$, we predict that $\hat{Y} = 20$, with $95\%$ CI of $[-3.58, 43.58]$.

Check-in: what assumption does this make?¶

More concretely: if we want to attach a CI to our prediction using $S_{Y|X}$, what are we assuming about our residuals?

Check-in: what assumption does this make?¶

More concretely: if we attach a CI this way to our prediction using $S_{Y|X}$, what are we assuming about our residuals?

Two key assumptions:

  1. Assume that residuals are normal, such that we can rely on same $z$-score values to calculate CI.
  2. Assume homoscedasticity, i.e., residuals are evenly distributed along regression line.

Assumption 2: Normality¶

Linear regression assumes normally distributed residuals.

  • This interpretation of $S_{Y|X}$ assumes the residuals of linear regression are normally distributed.
  • We also assume our parameter values $\beta$ are drawn from a normal distribution.
    • Particularly if we want to conduct a hypothesis test on those parameters (coming up later).

What about the variables themselves?

  • Normality of $X$ and $Y$ can help with interpretation (i.e., sometimes a very right-skewed distribution "distorts" our understanding of coefficients).
  • But it's actually not strictly necessary in a theoretical sense.

Assumption 3: Homoscedasticity¶

Homoscedasticity = residuals are evenly distributed along the regression line.

  • I.e., we assume that variance in $Y$ is uncorrelated with $X$.
  • Note that heteroscedasticity = residuals unevenly distributed along the regression line.

This matters for how we interpret $S_{Y|X}$.

  • Recall that $S_{Y|X}$ is an estimate of prediction error.
  • If residuals are unevenly distributed, $S_{Y|X}$ will sometimes be more accurate than others.

Heteroscedasticity in action¶

Heteroscedastic data often (but not always) has a tell-tale "funnel" shape.

In [10]:
np.random.seed(1)
X = np.arange(1, 101)

                         size = 100)

Brief interlude: Assumptions of linear regression¶

Assumption 4: Independence¶

  • A final assumption of (ordinary least squares) linear regression is independence.
  • Independence) means that each event or observation in our dataset if they do not affect each other, i.e., they were generated by distinct processes.
    • An example of non-independence would be multiple observations from the same subject.
  • In practice, lots of things are not independent.
  • This is one reason multilevel models are so useful (coming up on Day 5).

Recap of assumptions¶

We've discussed four critical assumptions:

  1. The relationship between $X$ and $Y$ is linear.
  2. The residuals are normally distributed.
  3. The residuals are homoscedastic.
  4. Our observations are independent.

Now, onto linear regression in Python!

Building our first model¶

  • Suppose we want to predict Age of Acquisition.
  • Intuitively, it seems like words about more "concrete" things (tables and chairs) should be learned earlier than more abstract things (justice and ideas).

Is this true?

Regression in Python¶

We can build a linear model using the statsmodels package.

import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
smf.ols(
    formula = ... ## model specifications as a string ("Y ~ X + ... ")
    data = ... ## which dataset to use
)

statsmodels in action¶

  • In our call to smf.ols, we specify that we want to fit the model.
  • This produces a fit model object.
In [87]:
mod = smf.ols(formula='AoA ~ Conc', data=df_words).fit()

Each parameter also gets a t-statistic¶

  • We can access these directly by calling mod.tvalues.
  • The t-statistic is simply the parameter divided by the standard error.

$\Large t = \frac{\beta_1}{SE_1}$

  • Note: This is how linear regression connects to NHST!

Each parameter also gets a p-value.¶

  • We can access these directly by calling mod.pvalues.
  • The p-value is the probability of obtaining a t-statistic at least that large, given the appropriate $t$-distribution.
    • $df = n - p$, where $p$ is number of parameters (including intercept).
    • I.e., just a good-old-fashioned t-test!

Interpreting our parameters¶

We could write this as a linear equation:

$\hat{Y} = 13.35 - 1.01*X_{conc}$

Interpretation:

  • The predicted AoA for words with zero concreteness is $13.35$.
  • With each 1-unit increase in Conc, predicted AoA drops by about 1 year.

Reporting our parameters¶

In an academic paper, you'd typically report your coefficients/parameters of interest in the following way:

Concreteness exhibited a significantly negative relationship with Age of Acquisition [$\beta = -1.01, SE = 0.02, p < .05]$.

You might also report the CI:

The $95\%$ confidence interval for the Concreteness coefficient was $[-1.04, -0.98]$.

Interpreting our results¶

  • We originally asked: are words about more concrete things learned earlier than words about abstract things?.
  • Based on these parameters, that seems true.
    • Words with higher concreteness are predicted to have a lower Aoa.
    • Importantly, the coefficient assigned to Conc is significantly negative ($p < .05$).
In [108]:
print("beta = {x}, p < .05)".format(x=round(mod.params['Conc'], 4)))

beta = -1.0079, p < .05)

Models as predictive¶

  • Recall that statistical models can also be used to predict data.
  • This is useful in a couple ways:
    • Practically, we might want to predict $\hat{Y}$ when we don't know the true value of $Y$.
    • Conceptually, our predictive success can tell us whether our model is a good one or not.
    • In turn, this might suggest we have a good model of the phenomenon we're interested in.
      • Always use caution here: correlation causation, and predictive success mechanistic insight.

Check-in: how could we quantify the success of our predictions?¶

Evaluating our predictions¶

There are a few ways to evaluate our model:

  • $S_{Y|X}$: estimated average prediction error.
  • $RSS$: sum of squared deviations between $Y$ and $\hat{Y}$.
  • $R^2$: an estimate of the proportion of variance explained.

We've already discussed the first two, so let's discuss $R^2$.

$R^2$: a measure of model fit¶

  • $R^2$: sometimes called the coefficient of determination.

$\Large R^2 = 1 - \frac{SS_{resid}}{SS_{total}}$

  • Decomposing the formula:
    • $SS_{resid} = RSS$: residual variance, i.e., what's "leftover" after accounting for the model?
    • $SS_{total} = SS_Y$: how much total variance is there to be "explained" in $Y$?
      • Equivalent to sum of squares of $Y$.
  • If $SS_{resid} = SS_{total}$, then model hasn't explained anything.
  • $1 - \frac{SS_{resid}}{SS_{total}}$: what proportion of total variance is explained by the model?

Calculating $R^2$¶

In [113]:
ss_resid = sum(mod.resid**2)
ss_resid
Out[113]:
155198.01950017206
In [114]:
ss_total = sum((df_words['AoA'] - df_words['AoA'].mean())**2)
ss_total
Out[114]:
181186.5585064583
In [115]:
r2 = 1 - ss_resid/ss_total
r2
Out[115]:
0.14343524829056176

Extracting $R^2$ using statsmodels¶

We can also extract $R^2$ from our fit model object.

Part 4: Categorical predictors¶

Why Categorical predictors?¶

  • So far, we've been assuming $X$ is continuous.
  • But we're often interested in categorical variables.
    • Smoking status (yes vs. no)
    • Spam status (spam vs. not spam).
    • Test result (positive vs. negative).
  • When we want to predict a (binary) categorical variable, we can use logistic regression (coming up).
  • But if we're still predicting a continuous variable, we can use linear regression.

Brief primer on categorical variables¶

  • Categorical variables are typically called factors.
  • Different categories of this variable are called levels.
    • E.g., spam vs. not spam are levels of the variable Spam Status.
  • For now, we'll focus on binary variables, but categorical variables often have 2 levels.

Dataset: word relatedness, in context¶

  • The same word (e.g., "lamb") can have different meanings in different contexts.

She liked the marinated lamb.

She liked the friendly lamb.

  • Trott & Bergen (2021) collected human judgments of how related these uses of the same wordform were in different contexts (dataset on GitHub).
  • We'll use this dataset to illustrate categorical predictors.
  • Note that this dataset will also be used in Part 2 of your lab.

Loading dataset¶

    • mean_relatedness: this is what we want to predict!
    • same: this tells us whether the two uses of a word belong to the same meaning (e.g., baseball bat vs. wooden bat) or different meanings (e.g., baseball bat vs. furry bat).

Categorical variables in a linear equation¶

Our linear equation takes the form:

$\Large \hat{Y} = 1.32 + 2.14X_{same}$

But what exactly does this mean?

Contrast coding¶

  • There are many ways to code a categorical variable in a regression model.
  • One of the most common approaches is called treatment coding.
  • For a binary variable, this means:
    • Treat each level of the variable as 1 (True) vs. 0 (e.g., False).
    • Select the mean of one level (e.g., 0) to be the intercept.
    • The slope then indicates the difference in means between the intercept and the other level (e.g., 1).

Treatment coding in the linear equation¶

First, we turn our same variable into 1 and 0:

$ \begin{equation} X= \begin{cases} 0, & \text{if}\ X=False \\ 1, & \text{if}\ X=True \\ \end{cases} \end{equation}$

Now, let's consider the linear equation once more:

$\Large \hat{Y} = 1.32 + 2.14X_{same}$

  • What happens when $X_{same = False}$?
  • What happens when $X_{same = True}$?

Treatment coding in the linear equation¶

$\Large \hat{Y} = 1.32 + 2.14X_{same}$

  • If $X_{same = False}$...
    • Our equation reduces to: $\hat{Y} = 1.32 + 2.14*0 = 1.32$
    • This is just the intercept, e.g., mean_relatedness when X = False.
  • If $X_{same = True}$...
    • Our equation reduces to: $\hat{Y} = 1.32 + 2.14*1 = 3.46$
    • This should be equal to mean_relatedness when X = True!

Checking our work¶

  • Let's inspect the mean of each level to make sure our numbers match up.
  • It looks like they do!
In [160]:
df_rawc[['same', 'mean_relatedness']].groupby('same').mean()
Out[160]:
mean_relatedness
same
False 1.321497
True 3.464674
